^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Nice play. If Mary bids 4@S (which is what I recommend) Judy still doubles and I assume Faye bids 5@D or 5@H. A double of 4@S is neither pure penalty nor pure takeout. |
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is the infamous and often dangerous "do something intelligent" double. It shows values but nothing specific. So partner has to figure out what to do. That is why we preempt, to make the opponents guess. And they often guess wrong.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It does say you have some tricks and are willing to play 4@S doubled but it is not pure penalty. Partner then can pass with a flat hand. In this board, in fact, with the @SK as a likely trick Faye could consider a pass especially if we were vul.|
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The 2 keys in deciding whether or not to pull a "do something intelligent double" are:
^c@2a) length and strength in the opps suit. The shorter you are in their suit, the more you want to bid. If you have a singleton or void, it is usually right to pull. 
^C@2The other reason is how balanced your hand is. The more balanced your hand, the less you want to bid, the more you want to sit. |
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But if you have a long suit of your own you might want to bid it. On this hand, had Judy doubled 4@S, Faye has a tough decision. She has a defensive trick in spades, which is a minus for pulling but she has two 5-card suits. |
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So had the auction gone 3@S-P-4@S-dbl-P-? I would probably decide to pull with Faye's hand given the vulnerability. And I would have bid 4NT which is NOT to play. It is, "partner I have 2 suits". The 2 suits are not necessarily clubs and diamonds because Judy's double does not explicitly promise hearts. |
PG| ***** 71 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is just any 2 suits. So Judy would pick the better of clubs and diamonds. If she picked diamonds, she must be prepared to have Faye bid hearts. On this hand had the auction gone that way, they end up in 5 diamonds.|
PG| ***** 72 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One other comment on the play. At trick 3 it is not clear that Mary should cover the @HJ, but if she does, then Faye goes down because I have the @HQ9 over the @H107 in dummy. This illustrates an important finesse principle. |
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You should be reluctant in general to lead an honor from your hand to finesse. The reason being, if the opponent covers, it takes 2 of your honors to knock out 1 of theirs. But on this hand it is not clear how to play the hearts to only lose 1 trick. The @HJ could be right if I am the one with the doubleton honor.|
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now why I did not bid 1@S as my hand meets Rule 20. I am sure our feisty Kibbers are still here. -:) At that vulnerability, with my nice spades and good 7-3-2-1 distribution, 4@S would not have been unreasonable as a preempt in 1st or 3rd seat.|
